# 'BlinkDigits' by Richard Langner
## Bink out numbers on a single LED.

Display any number from 0 to 99999. For example

- **3** is represented by briefly flashing three times, <br>
- **9** is represented by briefly flashing nine times, <br>
- **0** is represented by a long flash.<br><br>
After each digit there is a brief pause before the next digit is flashed.<br>
When all digits in your number have been flashed, there is a longer pause, and then it all repeats.
## How can BlinkDigits improve my project?
- Use as a heartbeat LED to indicate the status of the program.
- Indicate an analog reading
- Indicate a digital counter
- When connected to wifi, blink out the last 3 digits of the IP address, so you know where to find your device on your network.

## How to use FlashDigits



In your loop() add the BlinkDigits function, for example :<br>
`flasher1.blink ( D4, LOW, 1883 )`<br>
- **D4** is the pin number of the LED ( or use LED_BUILTIN ) <br>
- **LOW**  is set to define the level required to turn on the LED, ( use HIGH or LOW )<br>
- **1883** is the number you want to blink ( in the range of 0-99999 ).<br><br>
BlinkDigits returns 'true' when all the digits have been flashed. See **examples** for why this is useful.<br><br>
**Note** : BlinkDigits is non-blocking code, and does not use interrupts. Please ensure your code does not use blocking delays in loop() as this will mess up the blink timing.

## Example code
Here is a simple example which uses one line of code to blink out 23.<br>

```
#include "BlinkDigits.h"
BlinkDigits flasher1;
int ledPin = D4;
int myNumber=23;

void setup() {
	pinMode(ledPin, OUTPUT);`
}

void loop() {
    flasher1.blink(ledPin, LOW, myNumber);
}
```
Check the **examples** folder for a variety of uses.
### Leading zeros
If you want to blink out leading zeros, for example 023, simply state the number of places you want - using the 'width' parameter - in this case 3.

`flasher1.blink(ledPin, LOW, myNumber,3);`<br>
## All timings are adjustable.
 Blinking too fast for you to read? <br>
 Here we slow things right down.<br>
`flasher1.config(400,1500,800, 5000); // slower timings.`<br>
- &nbsp;400 : the on/off digit flash time,<br>
- 1500 : the zero digit's on time<br>
- &nbsp;800 : the delay between digits<br>
- 5000 : the delay before repeating the number.<br>
- Defaults are 200, 1000, 500, 3000.
